Note:
Wave STAGE1-HARDEN-LEXER regression test — Bug #371.

Context:
TOKEN_NEGATIVE (133) was previously omitted from
parser.token_can_be_identifier, so any source file that tried to bind
or reference the bare identifier `negative` was rejected at parse time
with "Expected identifier after Let". This blocked legitimate use of
`negative` as a variable name while keeping the prefix-operator form
`negative <INT>` (used pervasively in v0.0.8.5 source — see
error_context.runa, hash_utils.runa, format_utils.runa, mir/cfg.runa,
mir/ssa.runa, mir/optimizations/dead_store.runa, transformations/
trait_resolution.runa, internal/string_utils.runa).

Fix (Option A, context-sensitive disambiguation):
TOKEN_NEGATIVE was added to token_can_be_identifier so it is legal as
a Let-target / parameter / field identifier. It was NOT added to
token_can_continue_identifier, so a multi-word collector still stops
at `negative` and does not swallow the operator into a preceding
binding name. The expression-primary dispatch on TOKEN_NEGATIVE still
handles `negative <TOKEN_INTEGER>` as unary negation, unchanged.

Test cases:
  (1) `Let negative be 5`            — bare identifier `negative`
  (2) `Let is_negative be 1`         — identifier containing the
                                       substring (single token, lexed
                                       as one word via underscore
                                       continuation in the lexer's
                                       word-reader loop).
  (3) `Let x be negative 5`          — unary-negation expression form
                                       still works after the change.
  (4) `Set negative to negative 7`   — shadowing edge case: bare
                                       `negative` as a Set-target,
                                       with `negative <INT>` as the
                                       right-hand value, in a single
                                       statement.

Each check returns a unique non-zero exit code on failure so any
regression is precisely localizable. Exit 0 means all four cases
parsed AND evaluated correctly.
:End Note

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Note: Check 1 -- `negative` as a Let-target variable name.
    Let negative be 5
    If negative is not equal to 5:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Check 2 -- identifier containing the substring `negative`.
    Let is_negative be 1
    If is_negative is not equal to 1:
        Return 2
    End If

    Note: Check 3 -- unary negation prefix on an integer literal.
    Let x be negative 5
    Let neg_five be 0 minus 5
    If x is not equal to neg_five:
        Return 3
    End If

    Note: Check 4 -- shadowing edge case: rebind `negative` to the
    Note: unary-negation expression value. Both reads of `negative` on
    Note: the right side refer to operator-form `negative 7`, while
    Note: the Set target re-binds the bare identifier.
    Set negative to negative 7
    Let neg_seven be 0 minus 7
    If negative is not equal to neg_seven:
        Return 4
    End If

    Note: Check 5 -- arithmetic combining the bare identifier with the
    Note: prefix-operator form on the same line, exercising the
    Note: identifier-vs-operator disambiguation inside an expression
    Note: parse rather than a Let-target parse.
    Let combined be negative plus negative 3
    Let expected_combined be neg_seven plus 0 minus 3
    If combined is not equal to expected_combined:
        Return 5
    End If

    Return 0
End Process
